f=Shared OS/logical/ogilvy-creative-code.md · in=David Ogilvy (1911-1999), widely called "The Father Advertising," founded Ogilvy Mather built one world's largest agencies. His creative philosophy articulated *Confessions Advertising Man* (1963) *Ogilvy Advertising* (1983) combined empirical rigor, ethical clarity, unwavering belief "the consumer moron; she's your wife." extraction distills his rules testable creative code spark's art-direction-critique coherence-qa gates. Ogilvy's principles complemented Ries Trout's positioning laws (archive.org) Kotler's framework (Books/), which Ogilvy's work anticipated validated. · h2:PART OGILVY'S "HOW WRITE" MEMO (1982)=Ogilvy's famous internal memo Ogilvy Mather employees, September 1982. full text public domain through agency tradition. · h3:Commandments Business Writing=**Read Roman-Raphaelson book writing. Read three times.** **Write way you talk. Naturally.** Formal prose alienates; conversational prose persuades. **Use short words, short sentences, short paragraphs.** Ogilvy's copy averaged words sentence. **Never use jargon.** "Reconceptualize," "demassification," "attitudinally," "judgmentally" hallmarks pretense. Use plain English. **Never write two pages any subject.** takes two pages, you haven't thought about enough. **Check your quotations.** Misattributed quotes fireable offense. **Never send letter memo day you write it.** Read aloud next morning, edit. **If important, get colleague improve it.** writer needs editor. Even Ogilvy. **Before you send it, make sure crystal clear what you want recipient do.** communication specific call action. 10. **If you want ACTION, don't write. tell person what you want.** · h3:Spark's Application=\| Ogilvy Rule \| Spark's Test \| · h3:Spark's Application=\|------------\|-------------\| · h3:Spark's Application=\| #4 (No jargon) \| Does any sentence use a word not found in everyday speech? Flag it. \| · h3:Spark's Application=\| #7 (Read aloud, then edit) \| Would this creative survive reading aloud? If it sounds unnatural, it IS unnatural. \| · h3:Spark's Application=\| #9 (Clarity of action) \| Does the audience know exactly what to do next? Ambiguous CTA = failure. \| · h3:Spark's Application=\| #10 (Go tell them) \| For internal escalations: has this already been discussed in person before writing? \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=callable framework spark's gate. creative gets scored tests. test Ogilvy citation. · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| # \| Test \| Citation \| Pass Condition \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\|---\|------\|----------\|---------------\| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 1 \| **Consumer Respect** \| Ogilvy, Ch.1, p.7 \| No condescension. Audience treated as intelligent. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 2 \| **Big Idea** \| Ogilvy, Ch.1, pp.13-17 \| Passes ≥4 of 5 Big Idea signs (gasp/unique/strategic/fit/timeless). \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 3 \| **Specific Fact** \| Ogilvy, Ch.1, p.20 \| At least one specific, verifiable fact that could not describe a competitor. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 4 \| **Headline Has Benefit + Brand + Specificity** \| Ogilvy, Ch.5, pp.73-74 \| Headline contains benefit OR news, brand name, and a specific claim. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 5 \| **Research-Backed** \| Ogilvy, Ch.1, p.12 \| Creative cites research source or product knowledge. No research = auto-fail. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 6 \| **Promise Type** \| Ogilvy, Ch.1, pp.21-24 \| At least one of 5 promise types is explicit. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 7 \| **No Boredom** \| Ogilvy, Ch.1, p.32 \| No unsubstantiated superlatives. No company-first opening. No "solution" word. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 8 \| **Jargon-Free** \| Ogilvy Memo (1982), #4 \| All words are everyday English. Jargon → flagged. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 9 \| **Reads Aloud Naturally** \| Ogilvy Memo (1982), #7 \| Read aloud test: sounds like conversation, not press release. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=\| 10 \| **Clear Call to Action** \| Ogilvy Memo (1982), #9 \| Audience knows exactly what to do next. Single, unambiguous action. \| · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=**Scoring:** · h2:PART CREATIVE CODE ENFORCEMENT (Spark's Test Battery)=10/10: Ogilvy-Grade Creative. Ship immediately., 8-9/10: Strong. Fix 1-2 failures re-submit., 6-7/10: Needs significant revision. least Ogilvy rules violated., ≤5/10: Reject. Return concept stage. · h2:BOUNDARIES WITH OTHER SCRIPTS=**marketing_laws.py:** Ogilvy's rules 1-3 (Consumer Respect, Big Idea, Specificity) operationalize Cialdini's Liking Authority. Ogilvy Cialdini together determine whether creative persuade., **aaker-brand-equity.md:** Ogilvy's "brand image" concept (1963) foundation Aaker's brand equity model (1995). Ogilvy Ch.1 Aaker Ch.3., **binet-field-effectiveness.md:** Binet Field's IPA data validates Ogilvy empirically: emotional (brand-building) advertising produces 2-3× long-term business effects rational (activation) advertising. Ogilvy's "Big Idea" campaigns emotional half., **lena's humanic-writing skill:** Rules 3-5 Ogilvy's Don't-Bore principle (1963) original anti-AI-writing rules lena's skill operationalizes., **spark's art-direction-critique:** creative code COMES Ogilvy. 1-10 axes calibrated against Oglivy's 10-pass test battery.